      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm trying to prototype a ray tracer in python and i'm struggling with the reflection math. can you write a function that takes an incident vector and a surface normal and returns the reflection vector? \n\ni have some test cases i need to pass to make sure the math is right. here they are:\n\n```python\ndef test_reflection():\n    # Test case 1: simple 45 degree reflection\n    # Incident: [1, -1, 0], Normal: [0, 1, 0] -> Expected: [1, 1, 0]\n    I1 = [1, -1, 0]\n    N1 = [0, 1, 0]\n    R1 = reflect(I1, N1)\n    assert R1 == [1, 1, 0], f\"Expected [1, 1, 0], got {R1}\"\n\n    # Test case 2: perpendicular hit\n    # Incident: [0, -1, 0], Normal: [0, 1, 0] -> Expected: [0, 1, 0]\n    I2 = [0, -1, 0]\n    N2 = [0, 1, 0]\n    R2 = reflect(I2, N2)\n    assert R2 == [0, 1, 0], f\"Expected [0, 1, 0], got {R2}\"\n\n    # Test case 3: diagonal hit\n    # Incident: [-1, -1, 0], Normal: [0, 1, 0] -> Expected: [-1, 1, 0]\n    I3 = [-1, -1, 0]\n    N3 = [0, 1, 0]\n    R3 = reflect(I3, N3)\n    assert R3 == [-1, 1, 0], f\"Expected [-1, 1, 0], got {R3}\"\n\n    print(\"all tests passed!\")\n\nreflect(None, None) # placeholder\ntest_reflection()\n```\n\ncan you just write the `reflect` function for me so i can get this running? thanks",
